    <summary>Bitcoin developer Rusty Russell shared the results of Mike Schmidt's testing of various software and services with v1 addresses using the original BIP341 specification. Notable findings include some platforms not supporting it, while others failed address validation or encountered errors during the sending process. In response to this, Pieter Wuille suggested that there was no reason to maintain the old-software-can-send-to-future-segwit-versions property. Other developers proposed alternate solutions, including a survey to see which wallets already provide forward compatibility and the possibility of introducing length restrictions or a new checksum scheme. Additionally, Pieter Wuille suggested that there may be other uses for extra bytes in v1 addresses. Several proposals have been made regarding length restrictions for future segwit versions. One proposal suggests using a new checksum scheme unless the first byte is 0, while another proposal suggests length restrictions for future segwits to be either 10, 13, 16, 20, 23, 26, 29, 32, 36, or 40 bytes. The former proposal is backwards incompatible and only succeeds 1 in a billion, but it is preferred by some because it forces upgrades. The latter proposal is backwards compatible and old code still works, but it restricts future segwit versions and may require new encoding if a different length is needed. It is suggested that a decision be reached soon so that software can be upgraded for a taproot world.Pieter Wuille has shared a BIP341 witness v1 address that corresponds to the generator as an inner public key, using TapTweak(pubkey) as suggested by the BIP. However, c-lightning and Phoenix rejected the address, citing errors in parsing or invalid data, while Green and blockchain.info accepted it. Rusty Russell noted the results and encouraged others to explore this further.In an email exchange between David A. Harding and Pieter Wuille, there was discussion about retesting previously failed or stuck Bitcoin transactions that may have been successful if the backend infrastructure had upgraded to Bitcoin Core version 0.19 or higher. They both agreed that it would be beneficial to retest these transactions, given that over a year had passed since the release of version 0.19.Mike Schmidt expressed his willingness to retest services listed by Harding for v1 send support, while inviting suggestions for testing additional services that would be valuable. Rusty Russell wants to hear from services that currently support v1+ and whether they prefer option 1 or 2.Pieter Wuille proposed an alternative to length restrictions suggested by Russell in a GitHub pull request. He suggests using a variant proposed by Sipa unless the first byte is 0, while introducing a new checksum scheme with improved error detection capabilities.In an email thread on potential upgrades to the backend infrastructure, Pieter Wuille proposed an alternative to length restrictions for Bech32's checksum algorithm. He suggests using a variant proposed by Sipa unless the first byte is 0. Additionally, he discussed introducing a new checksum scheme that can detect up to 4 substitution errors. The thread also discussed the possibility of changing the checksum unconditionally for witness version 1 (v1) addresses. Based on survey results showing only two wallets correctly handled v1+ BIP173 addresses, David A. Harding and Pieter agreed to change the checksum for v1+ addresses.Rusty Russell provided corrected addresses for transactions that were initially posted incorrectly due to PEBKAC errors. The corrected addresses were accepted by Green and blockchain.info, but c-lightning and Phoenix could not parse the destination address or returned invalid data messages.Pieter Wuille proposed an alternative to length restrictions suggested in BIPs PR #945. He suggests using the checksum change based on the first byte, unless the first byte is 0. There are two proposals discussed in this thread: Length restrictions and Checksum change based on the first byte. Rusty prefers the second proposal as it forces upgrades since it breaks so clearly. However, David A. Harding also agrees with the first proposal since widespread support for bech32 addresses took a lot of community effort to get. Pieter Wuille is considering two options for the future of v1 receivers - continuing to use v1 or upgrading to a new version.Recently, the sender faced some issues while sending Bitcoin test transactions, where Green wallet segwit v1 send resulted in funds being sent to the wrong address and Blockchain.com's wallet also behaved similarly. Bitgo accepts a v1 send address but then a "Server error" during send occurs. Coinbase (web) reported on the final step of sending: Your send failed Please enter a valid email or Bitcoin address. In conclusion, the need for additional consensus restrictions for future upgrades is being debated.Pieter Wuille, a Bitcoin developer, has shared a BIP341 witness v1 address that corresponds to the generator as an inner public key. The tweak used is TapTweak(pub</summary>
